-- Japan, China, Taiwan, Singapore, Malaysia: Asia Bond, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-06-22T22:28:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-22/japan-china-taiwan-singapore-malaysia-asia-bond-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 Bank of Japan Governor Masaaki Shirakawa will give a
speech at an annual meeting of Japan’s credit cooperatives at
3:30 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
fell three basis points to 1.190 percent, according to Japan
Bond Trading Co., the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 90.52 per dollar at 7:22 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The finance ministry plans to sell 28 billion yuan
($4.1 billion) of 10-year bonds today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due May 2020 was 3.37
percent, according to the National Interbank Funding center.
The yuan was at 6.8187 per dollar.  
 India: The central bank will sell 20 billion rupees ($434
million) of 91-day treasury bills and 10 billion rupees of 182-
day treasury bills today.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.57
percent. The rupee was at 46.25.  
 South Korea: The government plans to raise as much as 340
billion won ($287 million) by selling 10-year inflation-linked
bonds tomorrow.  
 The yield on South Korea’s 4.5 percent bond due in March
2015 was 4.50 percent. The won was at 1,182.  
 Taiwan: Industrial production rose 31.94 percent in May,
compared with an increase of 31.38 percent in April, according
to a Bloomberg survey before the Ministry of Economic Affairs
releases the data today.  
 The yield on the 1.375 percent bond maturing in March 2020
was 1.44 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market. The
Taiwan dollar was at NT$31.82.  
 Thailand: The government will sell 7 billion baht ($216
million) of 2024 bonds and 3 billion baht of debt maturing in
2040 today. The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in
June 2019 was 3.13 percent. The baht was at 32.35.  
 Malaysia: The central bank plans to sell 1 billion ringgit
($312 million) of 61-day Islamic notes and 1 billion ringgit of
210-day notes.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent note due November 2019 was
4.02 percent. The ringgit was at 3.2075.  
 Singapore: The Department of Statistics will release
inflation data for May. Consumer prices rose 3 percent last
month, according to a Bloomberg survey. That would compare with
an increase of 3.2 percent in April.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.53 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3858.  
